Note:
Runa Runtime Integration Test: Language Keywords and Standard Library

This test validates that the runtime can successfully execute Runa code
using language keywords and standard library functions.

Test Coverage:
- Language keyword execution (Display, Length, etc.)
- Standard library function calls
- Type system integration
- End-to-end program execution
:End Note

Note: Import dependencies
Import "../../../src/compiler/driver.runa"
Import "../../../src/modules/stdlib/stubs/core_types.runa"
Import "../../../src/modules/stdlib/collections/list.runa"

Note: Test Suite Setup
Process called "run_runtime_integration_tests":
    Note: Run all runtime integration tests
    Print "Running Runtime Integration Tests..."
    
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0
    Let failed_count be 0
    
    Note: Test Language Keywords
    Let language_keywords_result be test_language_keywords
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If language_keywords_result.success:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        Print "  ✅ Language Keywords: PASSED"
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Print "  ❌ Language Keywords: FAILED"
        Print "     Error: " plus language_keywords_result.error
    
    Note: Test Standard Library Functions
    Let stdlib_functions_result be test_stdlib_functions
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If stdlib_functions_result.success:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        Print "  ✅ Standard Library Functions: PASSED"
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Print "  ❌ Standard Library Functions: FAILED"
        Print "     Error: " plus stdlib_functions_result.error
    
    Note: Test Type System Integration
    Let type_system_result be test_type_system_integration
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If type_system_result.success:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        Print "  ✅ Type System Integration: PASSED"
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Print "  ❌ Type System Integration: FAILED"
        Print "     Error: " plus type_system_result.error
    
    Note: Test End-to-End Execution
    Let end_to_end_result be test_end_to_end_execution
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If end_to_end_result.success:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        Print "  ✅ End-to-End Execution: PASSED"
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Print "  ❌ End-to-End Execution: FAILED"
        Print "     Error: " plus end_to_end_result.error
    
    Note: Test Performance
    Let performance_result be test_runtime_performance
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If performance_result.success:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        Print "  ✅ Runtime Performance: PASSED"
    Otherwise:
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        Print "  ❌ Runtime Performance: FAILED"
        Print "     Error: " plus performance_result.error
    
    Note: Test Summary
    Print "📊 Runtime Integration Test Summary:"
    Print "  Total Tests: " plus test_count
    Print "  Passed: " plus passed_count
    Print "  Failed: " plus failed_count
    Print "  Success Rate: " plus ((passed_count divided by test_count) multiplied by 100) plus "%"
    
    Return dictionary containing:
        "success" as failed_count is equal to 0
        "total_tests" as test_count
        "passed_tests" as passed_count
        "failed_tests" as failed_count

Note: Language Keywords Test
Process called "test_language_keywords" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test that the runtime can execute language keywords
    Let source_code be """
Note: Test language keywords execution
Let numbers (List[Integer]) be list containing 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
Let count (Integer) be length of numbers
Display "List length: "
Display count

Let text (String) be "Hello, Runa!"
Let text_length (Integer) be length of text
Display "Text length: "
Display text_length

Let data (Dictionary[String, Integer]) be dictionary with "x" as 10 and "y" as 20
Let dict_length (Integer) be length of data
Display "Dictionary length: "
Display dict_length

Let first_item (Integer) be numbers[0]
Display "First item: "
Display first_item

Let value (Optional[Integer]) be data["x"]
Display "Dictionary value: "
Display value
"""
    
    Let result be compile_and_run with source as source_code
    
    If not result.success:
        Return dictionary containing "success" as false and "error" as "Language keywords test failed: " plus result.error
    
    Return dictionary containing "success" as true

Note: Standard Library Functions Test
Process called "test_stdlib_functions" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test that the runtime can execute standard library functions
    Let source_code be """
Note: Test standard library functions execution
Let numbers (List[Integer]) be list containing 5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3

Let sorted_numbers (List[Integer]) be sort_list with list as numbers
Display "Sorted numbers: "
Display sorted_numbers

Let reversed_numbers (List[Integer]) be reverse_list with list as numbers
Display "Reversed numbers: "
Display reversed_numbers

Let sum_total (Integer) be sum_list with list as numbers
Display "Sum: "
Display sum_total

Let average_val (Float) be average_list with list as numbers
Display "Average: "
Display average_val

Let min_val (Optional[Integer]) be min_list with list as numbers
Display "Minimum: "
Display min_val

Let max_val (Optional[Integer]) be max_list with list as numbers
Display "Maximum: "
Display max_val

Let filtered_numbers (List[Integer]) be filter_list with list as numbers and predicate as is_even
Display "Even numbers: "
Display filtered_numbers

Let doubled_numbers (List[Integer]) be map_list with list as numbers and function as double_number
Display "Doubled numbers: "
Display doubled_numbers
"""
    
    Let result be compile_and_run with source as source_code
    
    If not result.success:
        Return dictionary containing "success" as false and "error" as "Standard library functions test failed: " plus result.error
    
    Return dictionary containing "success" as true

Note: Type System Integration Test
Process called "test_type_system_integration" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test that the runtime properly handles type system integration
    Let source_code be """
Note: Test type system integration
Let mixed_list (List[Any]) be list containing 42, "hello", true, 3.14

For each item in mixed_list:
    Let item_type (String) be type_of with value as item
    Display "Item: "
    Display item
    Display "Type: "
    Display item_type

Let optional_value (Optional[Integer]) be None
Let is_none_result (Boolean) be is_none with value as optional_value
Display "Is None: "
Display is_none_result

Let string_value (String) be "123"
Let converted_int (Optional[Integer]) be to_integer with value as string_value
Display "Converted integer: "
Display converted_int

Let float_value (Float) be 3.14159
Let converted_string (String) be to_string with value as float_value
Display "Converted string: "
Display converted_string
"""
    
    Let result be compile_and_run with source as source_code
    
    If not result.success:
        Return dictionary containing "success" as false and "error" as "Type system integration test failed: " plus result.error
    
    Return dictionary containing "success" as true

Note: End-to-End Execution Test
Process called "test_end_to_end_execution" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test complete end-to-end program execution
    Let source_code be """
Note: Test complete end-to-end program execution
Process called "calculate_statistics" that takes numbers (List[Integer]) returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Let stats be dictionary with:
        "count" as length of numbers
        "sum" as sum_list with list as numbers
        "average" as average_list with list as numbers
        "min" as min_list with list as numbers
        "max" as max_list with list as numbers
    
    If length of numbers is greater than 0:
        Let sorted_nums (List[Integer]) be sort_list with list as numbers
        Set stats["sorted"] to sorted_nums
        
        Let even_nums (List[Integer]) be filter_list with list as numbers and predicate as is_even
        Set stats["even_count"] to length of even_nums
    
    Return stats

Process called "is_even" that takes number (Integer) returns Boolean:
    Return number modulo 2 is equal to 0

Process called "main":
    Let test_data (List[Integer]) be list containing 15, 7, 23, 8, 12, 4, 19, 6
    
    Display "Original data: "
    Display test_data
    
    Let statistics (Dictionary[String, Any]) be calculate_statistics with numbers as test_data
    
    Display "Statistics:"
    Display "  Count: "
    Display statistics["count"]
    Display "  Sum: "
    Display statistics["sum"]
    Display "  Average: "
    Display statistics["average"]
    Display "  Min: "
    Display statistics["min"]
    Display "  Max: "
    Display statistics["max"]
    Display "  Sorted: "
    Display statistics["sorted"]
    Display "  Even count: "
    Display statistics["even_count"]
"""
    
    Let result be compile_and_run with source as source_code
    
    If not result.success:
        Return dictionary containing "success" as false and "error" as "End-to-end execution test failed: " plus result.error
    
    Return dictionary containing "success" as true

Note: Runtime Performance Test
Process called "test_runtime_performance" returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Test runtime performance with complex operations
    Let source_code be """
Note: Test runtime performance
Process called "generate_large_list" that takes size (Integer) returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list containing
    For i from 1 to size:
        add with list as result and item as i
    Return result

Process called "complex_operations" that takes data (List[Integer]) returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Let start_time be get_current_time_ms
    
    Let doubled (List[Integer]) be map_list with list as data and function as double_number
    Let filtered (List[Integer]) be filter_list with list as doubled and predicate as is_even
    Let sorted_data (List[Integer]) be sort_list with list as filtered
    Let reversed_data (List[Integer]) be reverse_list with list as sorted_data
    Let unique_data (List[Integer]) be unique_list with list as reversed_data
    
    Let end_time be get_current_time_ms
    Let execution_time be end_time minus start_time
    
    Return dictionary with:
        "result" as unique_data
        "execution_time_ms" as execution_time
        "input_size" as length of data
        "output_size" as length of unique_data

Process called "double_number" that takes number (Integer) returns Integer:
    Return number multiplied by 2

Process called "is_even" that takes number (Integer) returns Boolean:
    Return number modulo 2 is equal to 0

Process called "main":
    Let large_list (List[Integer]) be generate_large_list with size as 1000
    
    Display "Processing list of size: "
    Display length of large_list
    
    Let result (Dictionary[String, Any]) be complex_operations with data as large_list
    
    Display "Performance Results:"
    Display "  Input size: "
    Display result["input_size"]
    Display "  Output size: "
    Display result["output_size"]
    Display "  Execution time: "
    Display result["execution_time_ms"]
    Display " ms"
"""
    
    Let result be compile_and_run with source as source_code
    
    If not result.success:
        Return dictionary containing "success" as false and "error" as "Runtime performance test failed: " plus result.error
    
    Return dictionary containing "success" as true

